Let K denote the event that the card drawn is a king, and A be the event that the card drawn is an ace. We have to find P(KKA).
Now,
P(K) = \frac{4}{52}
Also, P(K | K) is the probability of the second king with the condition that one king has already been drawn. Now there are three kings in (52-1) = 51 cards.
Therefore,
P(K | K) = \frac{3}{51}
Lastly, P(A | KK) is the probability of the third drawn card to be an ace, with the condition that two kings have already been drawn. Now there are four aces in the remaining 50 cards.
Therefore,
P(A | KK) = \frac{4}{50}
By the multiplication law of probability, we have
P(KKA) = P(K) * P(K | K) * P(A | KK) = \frac{4}{52} * \frac{3}{51} * \frac{4}{50} = \frac{2}{5525}

